10pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">xii</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 250%;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark41">Chapter 1 Introduction</a><a name="bookmark45">&zwnj;</a></h1><ol id="l30"><ol id="l31"><li data-list-text="1.1"><h3 style="padding-top: 16pt;padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark42">Background</a><a name="bookmark46">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">Cycling is a very old sport that has been practised and followed around the world for decades. It is great for building fitness and for keeping active, and often also serves as a means of transportation for commuting.  Cycling as a sport is often very social and competitive in nature as people would often cycle in large groups where they would compete between each other and with other groups.  It is this social and competitive nature that often attracts people to taking up cycling as a sport.</p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">In recent years, it has become very popular for cyclists to train indoors as this is often safer than cycling on busy city streets, it makes cycling less reliant on the weather and is more convenient. The problem is that indoor cycling can often be very boring and lonely.</p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">That is where Zwift comes in. Zwift is an online based virtual reality platform that allows indoor cyclists to virtually ride courses in the real world whilst communicating and competing with other people in real time through the platform. It makes indoor training more social and less boring.</p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">In order to use the Zwift platform, you need a compatible trainer or training device in order to send riding information to Zwift and to receive feedback that will adjust the riding experience based on the virtual circumstances.  These trainers are very expensive and thus not very accessible to many consumers.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s8" style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">1</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">This project will aim to convert a non-compatible cheap trainer to be Zwift compatible through hardware and software development and implementation. The project, conducted by Mr DC.Eksteen as part of Mechatronic Project 475, stems from a proposal from Prof G.Venter.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="1.2"><h3 style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark43">Aim and Objectives</a><a name="bookmark47">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">The aim of the project is to modify and add to a cheap trainer to enable Zwift compatibility. The objectives will be to:</p><ul id="l32"><li data-list-text="•"><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -10pt;text-align: left;">Develop Hardware to:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ol id="l33"><li data-list-text="1."><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -14pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">Monitor and measure the rider inputs. These include, for example, cycling speed, cadence, power, heart rate etc.</p></li><li data-list-text="2."><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -14pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">Change the riding conditions based on feedback from Zwift platform. These include, for example, rolling resistance, incline etc.</p></li></ol></li><li data-list-text="•"><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -10pt;text-align: left;">Develop Software to:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ol id="l34"><li data-list-text="1."><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -14pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">Collect and process rider inputs and to communicate this to the Zwift platform.</p></li><li data-list-text="2."><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -14pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">Receive feedback information from Zwift and enable hardware to change the riding conditions as mentioned above.</p></li></ol></li><li data-list-text="•"><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -10pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">Combine developed Hardware and Software to produce a smart trainer that is comparable to smart trainers that are available on the market, but at a lower cost point. (Needs refinement)</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li></ul></li><li data-list-text="1.3"><h3 style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark44">Motivation</a><a name="bookmark48">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Motivation will focus on:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ul id="l35"><li data-list-text="•"><p style="padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -10pt;text-align: left;">What:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ul id="l36"><li data-list-text="–"><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -11pt;text-align: left;">Zwift = popular indoor training and competitive platform.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="–"><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -11pt;line-height: 140%;text-align: left;">Bicycle trainer = Convenient way to train cycling without needing to cycle outside.</p></li></ul></li><li data-list-text="•"><p style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -10pt;text-align: left;">Why:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ul id="l37"><li data-list-text="–"><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -11pt;text-align: left;">Indoor training increasing in popularity.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="–"><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -11pt;line-height: 140%;text-align: left;">Making access to Zwift more accessible and thus promoting cycling and exercise.</p></li></ul></li><li data-list-text="•"><p style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -10pt;text-align: left;">How:</p></li></ul></li></ol></ol><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ul id="l38"><li data-list-text="–"><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -11pt;text-align: left;">Convert existing &quot;dumb&quot; trainer into smart trainer.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="–"><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -11pt;text-align: left;">Enable trainer to connect with Zwift platform.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="–"><p style="padding-left: 102pt;text-indent: -11pt;line-height: 140%;text-align: left;">Using and leveraging existing industry standards to produce a robust solution.</p></li></ul><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 250%;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark49">Chapter 2 Literature Review</a><a name="bookmark60">&zwnj;</a></h1><p style="padding-top: 11pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">The literature review is performed to define the requirements for the connection with Zwift, as well as discovering and understanding the various desired and required features and products that exist on the market today.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ol id="l39"><ol id="l40"><li data-list-text="2.1"><h3 style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark50">Overview</a><a name="bookmark61">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s8" style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">4</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="2.2"><h3 style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark51">Zwift: Technology and Requirements</a><a name="bookmark62">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">As mentioned above, Zwift uses real-time training data to drive the avatar in the virtual world. In order to achieve this, Zwift needs to run on a device that has :</p><ul id="l41"><li data-list-text="•"><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -10pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark15" class="a">An internet connection to connect to the Zwift servers via the Application Program Interface (</a>API).</p></li><li data-list-text="•"><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -10pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">Bluetooth Low Energy (</a>BLE) or ANT+ functionality to receive the data from the training session.</p></li></ul><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark114" class="a">This device is usually a laptop, mobile phone or tablet, and will also display the avatar in the virtual world to the player. Moving forward, this device will be referred to as the &quot;host&quot; device as it is the central device controlling the user experience. (von Bromley, </a>2022)</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ol id="l42"><li data-list-text="2.2.1"><p class="s26" style="padding-left: 90pt;text-indent: -42pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark52">Basic Requirements</a><a name="bookmark63">&zwnj;</a></p><p style="padding-top: 12pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">As mentioned above, Zwift requires real-time tracking data from the player in order to control the avatar. The interactiveness and accuracy of the experience greatly depends on the amount and nature of the data that is sent to the host device (also sometimes referred to as the ’main unit’).</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 87pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 1pt;text-align: left;"/><p style="padding-top: 7pt;padding-left: 93pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Requirement   Impact</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 87pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 1pt;text-align: left;"/><p style="padding-top: 7pt;padding-left: 93pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Speed data     Most  basic  data  requirement  and  is</p><p style="padding-top: 1pt;padding-left: 190pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">essential to the use of the Zwift platform.</p><p style="padding-top: 9pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: right;">Cadence data   Not essential for platform, but a feature</p><p style="padding-top: 1pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: right;">that many players prefer to have available.</p><p style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 93pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Power data     Not essential for platform, although it is</p><p style="padding-top: 1pt;padding-bottom: 4pt;padding-left: 190pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 113%;text-align: left;">the preferred metric that Zwift will use to measure the effort of the player.</p><p style="padding-left: 87pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 1pt;text-align: left;"/><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="2.2.2"><p class="s26" style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 90pt;text-indent: -42pt;text-align: left;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="s27" name="bookmark53">B</a>LE vs ANT+<a name="bookmark64">&zwnj;</a></p><p style="padding-top: 12pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">Both </a><a href="#bookmark28" class="a">BLE and ANT+ devices communicate using Ultra-High Frequency (</a>UHF) electromagnetic waves with frequencies around 2.4 GHz. The communication</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">also takes part over a small distance.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s8" style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">BLE for Fitness Devices</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s24" style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark17" class="a">BLE is one of two standards for Bluetooth communication that has been developed and maintained by Bluetooth Special Interest Group (</a><a href="#bookmark65" class="a">BSIG).</a>1<a href="#bookmark68" class="a">The specific details of the technology and standard is discussed in Section </a><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">2.4. For the sake of Zwift requirements, this section will look at the specific protocol of the </a><span class="p">BLE specification that Zwift supports.</span></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;"><a href="#bookmark17" class="a">In the past, when Zwift was just launched, all of the Bluetooth communication was performed using proprietary protocols provided by the manufacturers of trainers and training equipment as there has not yet been a standard protocol defined to handle Bluetooth communication of controllable sports equipment. On 14 February 2017, </a><a href="#bookmark21" class="a">BSIG adopted the Fittness Machine Data (</a><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">FTMS) protocol to the </a><a href="#bookmark22" class="a">BLE Generic ATTribute Profile (</a><a href="#bookmark21" class="a">GATT). Then, in late 2021 Zwift announced that they will be supporting FTMS in their latest update, and thus any new trainer that would like to interact with the Zwift platform would be required to follow the </a><a href="#bookmark71" class="a">FTMS protocol as is discussed in Section </a><a href="#bookmark115" class="a">2.4. (Zwift </a>Forums)</p><p style="padding-bottom: 2pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark66" class="a">Table </a><a href="#bookmark21" class="a">2.1 below shows the different commands within the </a>FTMS protocol that Zwift uses to control connected trainers. This can be deducted from the control modes that are available on the platform, and have been confirmed by a Zwift engineer on the official support forums.</p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 1pt;text-align: left;"/><p class="s29" style="padding-left: 59pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark65">1</a><a href="#bookmark18" class="s31">The other being Bluetooth Basic Rate/Enhanced Data Rate (</a><span class="s30">BR/EDR)</span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;"><a href="#bookmark21" class="a" name="bookmark66">Table 2.1: Zwift Supported </a>FTMS Commands</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark66" class="a">Depending on the type of workout that is being performed, Zwift will use the different control point commands listed in Table </a><a href="#bookmark27" class="a">2.1 above.  When the user is normally riding around within the Zwift world, it will send Indoor Bike Simulation (</a><a href="#bookmark74" class="a">SIM) parameter commands.  This is explained in more detail in Section </a>2.4. When the user is using the &quot;Workout Mode&quot;, Zwift has the option to engage &quot;ERG&quot; mode, where it will send a desired power target that the trainer should aim to maintain regardless of the speed. Thus the user can decide to go faster, with the trainer lowering the resistance, or go slower with the trainer having an increased resistance. Lastly, the user can adjust the resistance on their trainer from within the Zwift software, requiring Zwift to then send that specific command to the trainer.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li></ol></li><li data-list-text="2.3"><h3 style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark54">Existing Trainer Technology</a><a name="bookmark67">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="2.4"><h3 style="padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="s32" name="bookmark55">B</a>LE Communication<a name="bookmark68">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark69" class="a">BLE works by forming pico - and scatter-net networks between various master and slave devices. Each device in the network is either a master or a slave, but never both. The devices then form a piconet when one or more slaves connect and synchronize with a single master device. The role of the master device is then to manage the slave devices through the protocol. This forms a network as can be seen in Figure </a>2.1 below.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 67pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="474" height="313" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="a" name="bookmark69">Figure 2.1: </a>BLE Star Network Topology</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">The master thus determines how often a slave is allowed to communicate, and slaves only communicate when requested to do so by a master. This is with one exception in the case of &quot;advertising&quot;. Advertising is a feature that allows a slave device to announce that it has something to transmit to the master. This is either an event message or a measurement value.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"/><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 110pt;text-indent: -63pt;line-height: 284%;text-align: left;"><a href="#bookmark70" class="a" name="bookmark70">Some other features worth considering are listed in Table </a><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">2.2 below: Table 2.2: Technical Specifications of the </a>BLE Standard</p><p style="padding-left: 72pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 12pt;text-align: left;">Description   Specification    Detail</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 66pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 1pt;text-align: left;"/><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 72pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">Data Package Size</p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 14pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">64 bit (min) to 216 bit (max)</p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 24pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">The size of any single data package that can be sent between a master and slave(s).</p><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 72pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">Data Transfer Rate</p><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 110pt;text-indent: -97pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">1 Mbps       The rate at which the data is typically transferred between devices.</p><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 72pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Security     128-bit AES     Security and encryption varies in</p><p style="padding-top: 5pt;padding-left: 252pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">levels, but generally data is encrypted between devices with a &quot;shared secret&quot; key that is generated during pairing.</p><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 252pt;text-indent: -179pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">Latency     6 ms         Time between device starting transmission and data getting transferred. name="bookmark82">Chapter 3</a><a name="bookmark85">&zwnj;</a></h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Software Development</h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 21pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark24" class="a">The software that was developed for this project was written in Python 3, using Visual Studio Code Integrated Development Environment (</a>IDE). The software was then deployed on a Raspberry Pi 3 B+ computer.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s8" style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">14</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><ol id="l43"><ol id="l44"><li data-list-text="3.1"><h3 style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark83">Structure</a><a name="bookmark86">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;">The software for the project has been written to form a very modular structure with separate &quot;handlers&quot; being written/developed for different functions of the greater application.  There are some exceptions where existing libraries and servers were used, but these are referenced in the relevant sections later in this chapter.</p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark87" class="a">Figure </a>3.1 below shows the modular structure that was implemented for the control of the Raspberry Pi 3B+ single-board computer</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 56pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="508" height="290" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;"><a name="bookmark87">Figure 3.1: Overview of General Software Structure</a></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="3.2"><h3 style="padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: -37pt;text-align: left;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="s32" name="bookmark84">B</a>LE Handler<a name="bookmark88">&zwnj;</a></h3></li></ol></ol><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">The BLE handler is responsible for all of the Bluetooth communication protocols, and has to strictly conform to the </a>BLE specifications in order to ensure compatibility with common devices.  The handler consists of a few different services that in tern manage some service or function within the greater protocol.</p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 13pt;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">The </a>BLE protocol was designed to be used with various layers of abstraction</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark89" class="a">between the low level operations of the system. This results in the structure for the abstraction layers as seen in Figure </a>3.2 below:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 147pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="249" height="426" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span></p><p style="padding-top: 9pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;"><a href="#bookmark16" class="a" name="bookmark89">Figure 3.2: </a>BLE Protocol Stack</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark25" class="a">The abstraction all the way up to the host already exists and is implemented on the Raspberry Pi. The D-Bus is an Inter-Process Communicationt (</a><a href="#bookmark29" class="a">IPC) method that allows for Remote Procedure Calls (</a><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">RPC) between the various processes. The role of the </a><a href="#bookmark109" class="a">BLE Interface Handler is thus to handle communication between the main process and Bluez. Bluez is the official Linux Bluetooth protocol stack, and is what controls the Bluetooth operations of the system. (Lee, </a>2020)</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark21" class="a">The </a><a href="#bookmark23" class="a">FTMS and Device Information Service (</a><a href="#bookmark16" class="a">DIS) Interpreters receive and send various BLE commands, requests and replies between the </a>BLE Interface Handler and the running application. It is here where messages are split up into their</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 142%;text-align: left;">various components before being acted apron, and replies get created in the required format before being sent to the Bluez stack.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 47pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark90">Chapter 4</a><a name="bookmark93">&zwnj;</a></h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align:
